at_pop2=3,500,000\n|stat_year3=1400\n|stat_area3=\n|stat_pop3=5,207,500\n--->\n|footnotes  =\n|today      = [[Vietnam]]<br>[[China]]<br>[[Laos]]\n}}\n\n{{History of Vietnam}}\nThe '''Tr\u1ea7n dynasty''' (Vietnamese: {{lang|vi|Nh\u00e0 Tr\u1ea7n}}; [[H\u00e1n-N\u00f4m|H\u00e1n N\u00f4m]]'':'' \u5bb6\u9673; [[H\u00e1n-Vi\u1ec7t|H\u00e1n Vi\u1ec7t]]: [[wikt:\u9673|\u9673]][[wikt:\u671d|\u671d]], ''Tr\u1ea7n tri\u1ec1u''<ref name=\"ed. Hall 2008\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=gyPjBevBHxcC&pg=PA159&dq=tran+fujian&hl=en&sa=X&ei=XiPNVPrfH4WgNsWpgagC&ved=0CD8Q6AEwBg#v=onepage&q=tran%20fujian&f=false ed. Hall 2008] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827072022/https://books.google.com/books?id=gyPjBevBHxcC&pg=PA159&dq=tran+fujian&hl=en&sa=X&ei=XiPNVPrfH4WgNsWpgagC&ved=0CD8Q6AEwBg#v=onepage&q=tran%20fujian&f=false |date=August 27, 2016 }}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=nZaaAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA159&dq=tran+fujian&hl=en&sa=X&ei=XiPNVPrfH4WgNsWpgagC&ved=0CDoQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=tran%20fujian&f=false p. 159] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160912092544/https://books.google.com/books?id=nZaaAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA159&dq=tran+fujian&hl=en&sa=X&ei=XiPNVPrfH4WgNsWpgagC&ved=0CDoQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=tran%20fujian&f=false |date=September 12, 2016 }}.</ref><ref name=\"books.google.com\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=ZHD4Asj0FagC&pg=PT90&dq=Tran+Chen+Fujian&hl=en&sa=X&ei=9AzMVM66BIfbsAShsIDgCQ&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=Tran%20Chen%20Fujian&f=false eds. Dutton & Werner & Whitmore 2013] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160825202215/https://books.google.com/books?id=ZHD4Asj0FagC&pg=PT90&dq=Tran+Chen+Fujian&hl=en&sa=X&ei=9AzMVM66BIfbsAShsIDgCQ&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=Tran%20Chen%20Fujian&f=false |date=August 25, 2016 }} [https://books.google.com/books?id=ZHD4Asj0FagC&pg=PT90&dq=tran+fujian&hl=en&sa=X&ei=di7NVJKXCovEggSwpYKgCQ&ved=0CEgQ6AEwCDg8#v=onepage&q=tran%20fujian&f=false .] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160821034624/https://books.google.com/books?id=ZHD4Asj0FagC&pg=PT90&dq=tran+fujian&hl=en&sa=X&ei=di7NVJKXCovEggSwpYKgCQ&ved=0CEgQ6AEwCDg8#v=onepage&q=tran%20fujian&f=false |date=August 21, 2016 }}</ref>) ruled [[Vietnam]] (then known as [[\u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t]] \u5927\u8d8a) from 1225 to 1400. The dynasty was founded when emperor [[Tr\u1ea7n Th\u00e1i T\u00f4ng]] ascended to the throne after his uncle [[Tr\u1ea7n Th\u1ee7 \u0110\u1ed9]] orchestrated the overthrow of the [[L\u00fd dynasty]]. The final emperor of the dynasty was [[Tr\u1ea7n Thi\u1ebfu \u0110\u1ebf|Thi\u1ebfu \u0110\u1ebf]], who at the age of five years was forced to abdicate the throne in favor of his maternal grandfather, [[H\u1ed3 Qu\u00fd Ly]]. The Tr\u1ea7n dynasty defeated three [[Mongol invasions of Vietnam|Mongol invasions]], most notably in the decisive [[Battle of B\u1ea1ch \u0110\u1eb1ng (1288)|Battle of B\u1ea1ch \u0110\u1eb1ng River]] in 1288.<ref name=\"Tran Dynasty \">{{cite web|publisher= Britannica.com|title=Tran Dynasty|url= https://www.britannica.com/topic/Tran-dynasty }}</ref>\n\nThe Tran improved Chinese [[gunpowder]]{{sfn|Tuyet Nhung Tran, Anthony J. S. Reid|2006|pp=89\u201390}} enabling them to expand southward to defeat and vassalize the [[Champa|Champa empire]].{{sfn|Tuyet Nhung Tran, Anthony J. S. Reid|2006|pp=75\u201377}} They also started using [[paper money]] for the first time in Vietnam.{{sfn|Chapuis|1998|p=95}}\n\nThe Tran dynasty was considered a golden age in Vietnamese language, arts, and culture;{{sfn|Terry E. Miller, Sean Williams|2008|p=249}} with the first pieces of [[Ch\u1eef N\u00f4m]] literature written during this period,<ref name=\":0\" /> and first-time introduction of the vernacular [[Vietnamese language]] into the court, alongside [[Chinese language|Chinese]].<ref name=\"lemanhthat\" /> This laid the foundation for the further development and solidifying of Vietnamese language and identity.\n\n==History==\n===Origin and foundation===\n{{see also|L\u00fd Chi\u00eau Ho\u00e0ng|Tr\u1ea7n Th\u1ee7 \u0110\u1ed9}}\n\nThe ancestors of the Tr\u1ea7n clan originated from the province of [[Fujian]] before they migrated under Tr\u1ea7n Kinh (\u9673\u4eac, Ch\u00e9n J\u012bng) to \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t, where their mixed-blooded descendants established the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty which ruled \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t. They were mixed-blooded due to many intermarriages between the Tr\u1ea7n and several royal members of the L\u00fd dynasty alongside members of their royal court. This was the case of [[Tr\u1ea7n L\u00fd]]<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.baomoi.com/ham-sac-to-trung-tu-tu-hai-minh/c/10426418.epi | title=Ham s\u1eafc, T\u00f4 Trung T\u1eeb t\u1ef1 h\u1ea1i m\u00ecnh | access-date=2017-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.bienkhoi.com/so-26/nha-tran.htm | title=Nh\u00e0 Tr\u1ea7n kh\u1edfi nghi\u1ec7p | access-date=2016-03-09}}</ref> and [[Tr\u1ea7n Th\u1eeba]], the latter whose son [[Tr\u1ea7n Th\u00e1i T\u00f4ng]] would later become the first emperor of the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty.<ref>{{cite book| title=A history of Vietnam: from Hong Bang to Tu Duc |last=Chapuis |first=Oscar |year=1995 |publisher=Greenwood Press |isbn=0-313-29622-7 |page=85}}</ref> Their{{Specify|reason=who?|date=November 2019}} descendants established the [[Tran dynasty]], which ruled Vietnam (Dai Viet). Some of the mixed-blooded descendants and certain members of the clan could still speak [[Chinese language|Chinese]], as when a [[Yuan dynasty]] envoy met with the Chinese-speaking Tran Prince [[Tr\u1ea7n Qu\u1ed1c Tu\u1ea5n]] in 1282.<ref name=\"Taylor 2013\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=6UHi9JXNokEC&pg=PA120&dq=tran+fujian&hl=en&sa=X&ei=XiPNVPrfH4WgNsWpgagC&ved=0CCQQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=tran%20fujian&f=false Taylor 2013], p. 120.</ref><ref name=\"ed. Hall 2008\"/><ref name=\"books.google.com\"/><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=6UHi9JXNokEC&pg=PA103#v=onepage&q&f=false Taylor 2013] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160912063710/https://books.google.com/books?id=6UHi9JXNokEC&pg=PA103#v=onepage&q&f=false |date=September 12, 2016 }}, p. 103.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=E10tnvapZt0C&pg=PA112&dq=tran+fujian&hl=en&sa=X&ei=XiPNVPrfH4WgNsWpgagC&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=tran%20fujian&f=false Gunn 2011] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160821080312/https://books.google.com/books?id=E10tnvapZt0C&pg=PA112&dq=tran+fujian&hl=en&sa=X&ei=XiPNVPrfH4WgNsWpgagC&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=tran%20fujian&f=false |date=August 21, 2016 }}, p. 112.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=cNwpAQAAMAAJ&q=tran+fujian&dq=tran+fujian&hl=en&sa=X&ei=1iPNVKSgKoS4ggTd6oDgCw&ved=0CCIQ6AEwATge Embree & Lewis 1988] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160821041346/https://books.google.com/books?id=cNwpAQAAMAAJ&q=tran+fujian&dq=tran+fujian&hl=en&sa=X&ei=1iPNVKSgKoS4ggTd6oDgCw&ved=0CCIQ6AEwATge |date=August 21, 2016 }}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=cNwpAQAAMAAJ&q=In+particular,+the+Tran+from+Fujian+in+South+China+had+built+up+their+power+in+the+southern+Red+River+delta+on+a+commercial+base+%28fishing%29.+Now+the+family+became+a+force+in+the+capital+by+intermarrying+with+the+Ly,+and+soon+it+took+the+throne+for+...&dq=In+particular,+the+Tran+from+Fujian+in+South+China+had+built+up+their+power+in+the+southern+Red+River+delta+on+a+commercial+base+%28fishing%29.+Now+the+family+became+a+force+in+the+capital+by+intermarrying+with+the+Ly,+and+soon+it+took+the+throne+for+...&hl=en&sa=X&ei=yCXNVP2-FcKPsQSTioCYCA&ved=0CB8Q6AEwAA p. 190.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160821101251/https://books.google.com/books?id=cNwpAQAAMAAJ&q=In+particular,+the+Tran+from+Fujian+in+South+China+had+built+up+their+power+in+the+southern+Red+River+delta+on+a+commercial+base+%28fishing%29.+Now+the+family+became+a+force+in+the+capital+by+intermarrying+with+the+Ly,+and+soon+it+took+the+throne+for+...&dq=In+particular,+the+Tran+from+Fujian+in+South+China+had+built+up+their+power+in+the+southern+Red+River+delta+on+a+commercial+base+%28fishing%29.+Now+the+family+became+a+force+in+the+capital+by+intermarrying+with+the+Ly,+and+soon+it+took+the+throne+for+...&hl=en&sa=X&ei=yCXNVP2-FcKPsQSTioCYCA&ved=0CB8Q6AEwAA |date=August 21, 2016 }}</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=0LgSI9UQNpwC&pg=PA8&dq=tran+fukien&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Fi_NVITUN6XjsASAvoKoDg&ved=0CFwQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=tran%20fukien&f=false Woodside 1971] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160821092734/https://books.google.com/books?id=0LgSI9UQNpwC&pg=PA8&dq=tran+fukien&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Fi_NVITUN6XjsASAvoKoDg&ved=0CFwQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=tran%20fukien&f=false |date=August 21, 2016 }}, p. 8.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=GaZvX2BzeegC&pg=PA121&lpg=PA121&dq=tran+dynasty+chinese&source=bl&ots=tQCG4IggsE&sig=dpbdIwdxFWGHn3epgk6KZXZeY-s&hl=en&sa=X&ei=3uo-VYG5G4iwsASflIHwDg&ved=0CDcQ6AEwCTgK#v=onepage&q=tran%20dynasty%20chinese&f=false Womack 2006] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160603062331/https://books.google.com/books?id=GaZvX2BzeegC&pg=PA121&lpg=PA121&dq=tran+dynasty+chinese&source=bl&ots=tQCG4IggsE&sig=dpbdIwdxFWGHn3epgk6KZXZeY-s&hl=en&sa=X&ei=3uo-VYG5G4iwsASflIHwDg&ved=0CDcQ6AEwCTgK#v=onepage&q=tran%20dynasty%20chinese&f=false |date=June 3, 2016 }}, p. 121.</ref><ref>[http://afe.easia.columbia.edu/timelines/vietnam_timeline.htm Vietnamese History: A Chronological Outline] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160510143439/http://afe.easia.columbia.edu/timelines/vietnam_timeline.htm |date=May 10, 2016 }}</ref> The first of the Tr\u1ea7n clan to live in [[\u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t]] was Tr\u1ea7n Kinh, who settled in T\u1ee9c M\u1eb7c village (now [[M\u1ef9 L\u1ed9c District|M\u1ef9 L\u1ed9c]], [[Nam \u0110\u1ecbnh]]) who lived by fishing.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=159}}<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=P2HP31kOSA4C&pg=PA120#v=onepage&q&f=false Taylor (2013), p. 120] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140627150022/https://books.google.com/books?id=P2HP31kOSA4C&pg=PA120#v=onepage&q&f=false |date=June 27, 2014 }}</ref> After three generations in \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t, the Tr\u1ea7n clan became a rich and powerful family under Tr\u1ea7n L\u00fd, who was Tr\u1ea7n Kinh's grandson.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=gyPjBevBHxcC&pg=PA159#v=onepage&q&f=false Hall (2008), p. 159] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160512203059/https://books.google.com/books?id=gyPjBevBHxcC&pg=PA159#v=onepage&q&f=false |date=May 12, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nDuring the troubled time under the reign of [[L\u00fd Cao T\u00f4ng]], the Crown Prince [[L\u00fd S\u1ea3m]] sought refuge in the family of Tr\u1ea7n L\u00fd and decided to marry his beautiful daughter [[Tr\u1ea7n Th\u1ecb Dung]] in 1209.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=153}} Afterward, it was the Tr\u1ea7n clan who helped L\u00fd Cao T\u00f4ng and L\u00fd S\u1ea3m restore the throne in [[Hanoi|Th\u0103ng Long]]. As a result, the Emperor appointed several members of the Tr\u1ea7n clan to high positions in the royal court, such as [[T\u00f4 Trung T\u1eeb]], who was an uncle of Tr\u1ea7n Th\u1ecb Dung, and [[Tr\u1ea7n T\u1ef1 Kh\u00e1nh]] and [[Tr\u1ea7n Th\u1eeba]], who were Tr\u1ea7n L\u00fd's sons.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=153}} In 1211 the Crown Prince L\u00fd S\u1ea3m was enthroned as [[L\u00fd Hu\u1ec7 T\u00f4ng]] after the death of [[L\u00fd Cao T\u00f4ng]]. By that time the Tr\u1ea7n clan's position began to rise in the royal court.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=154}}<ref>{{Harvnb|National Bureau for Historical Record|1998|p=186}}</ref>\n\nHaving been mentally ill for a long time, the Emperor [[L\u00fd Hu\u1ec7 T\u00f4ng]] ultimately decided to cede the throne of the [[L\u00fd dynasty]] to [[crown prince]]ss [[L\u00fd Chi\u00eau Ho\u00e0ng]] in October of the lunar calendar, 1224.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=156}} Ascending the throne at the age of only six, L\u00fd Chi\u00eau Ho\u00e0ng ruled under the total influence of the commander of the royal guard, Tr\u1ea7n Th\u1ee7 \u0110\u1ed9. Even the Empress Regnant's servants were chosen by Tr\u1ea7n Th\u1ee7 \u0110\u1ed9; one of them was his 7-year-old nephew [[Tr\u1ea7n C\u1ea3nh]].{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=157}} When Tr\u1ea7n C\u1ea3nh informed Tr\u1ea7n Th\u1ee7 \u0110\u1ed9 that the Empress Regnant seemed to have affection towards him, the leader of the Tr\u1ea7n clan immediately decided to take this chance to carry out his plot to overthrow the L\u00fd dynasty and establish a new dynasty ruled by his own clan. First Tr\u1ea7n Th\u1ee7 \u0110\u1ed9 moved the whole Tr\u1ea7n clan to the royal palace and arranged a secret marriage between L\u00fd Chi\u00eau Ho\u00e0ng and Tr\u1ea7n C\u1ea3nh there, without the appearance of any mandarin or member of the L\u00fd royal family. After that, he announced the ''fait accompli'' to the royal court and made L\u00fd Chi\u00eau Ho\u00e0ng cede the throne to her new husband on the grounds that she was incapable of holding office. Thus Tr\u1ea7n C\u1ea3nh was chosen as her successor. As a result, the 216-year reign of the L\u00fd dynasty was ended, and the new Tr\u1ea7n dynasty was created on the first day of the twelfth lunar month ([[Gregorian calendar|Gregorian]]: December 31) 1225.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|pp=157\u2013158}}{{sfn|Chapuis|1995|p=79}}\n\n===Early Tr\u1ea7n===\n{{see also|Tr\u1ea7n Th\u00e1i T\u00f4ng|Tr\u1ea7n Th\u00e1nh T\u00f4ng}}\nAfter the collapse of the L\u00fd Dynasty, Tr\u1ea7n Th\u1ee7 \u0110\u1ed9 was still afraid that the newly established Tr\u1ea7n Dynasty might be overthrown by its political opponents. He therefore continued to eliminate members of the L\u00fd royal family: first the former emperor L\u00fd Hu\u1ec7 T\u00f4ng in the tenth lunar month of 1226,{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=160}} then other members of the L\u00fd royal family were massacred by the order of Tr\u1ea7n Th\u1ee7 \u0110\u1ed9 in the eighth lunar month of 1232.<ref>{{Harvnb|National Bureau for Historical Record|1998|p=194}}</ref>{{sfn|Chapuis|1995|p=80}}{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=163}}\n\nTr\u1ea7n Th\u00e1i T\u00f4ng was enthroned when he was only eight-years-old. There were several rebellions in \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t at that time, so Tr\u1ea7n Th\u1ee7 \u0110\u1ed9 had to devote all of his efforts to consolidating the rule of Th\u00e1i T\u00f4ng in the royal court and over the country. Right after the coronation of the Emperor in 1226, [[Nguy\u1ec5n N\u1ed9n]] and [[\u0110o\u00e0n Th\u01b0\u1ee3ng]] rose in revolt in the mountainous region of [[B\u1eafc Giang]] and [[H\u1ea3i D\u01b0\u01a1ng]].{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=159}} By both military and diplomatic measures, such as sending an army and by awarding two leaders of the revolt the title of Prince ([[wikt:V\u01b0\u01a1ng|V\u01b0\u01a1ng]]), Tr\u1ea7n Th\u1ee7 \u0110\u1ed9 was able to put down this revolt in 1229.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|pp=161\u2013162}}{{sfn|Tr\u1ea7n Tr\u1ecdng Kim|1971|p=50}}\n\nAccording to ''[[\u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t s\u1eed k\u00fd to\u00e0n th\u01b0]]'', Th\u00e1i T\u00f4ng and his wife, the Empress [[L\u00fd Chi\u00eau Ho\u00e0ng|Chi\u00eau Th\u00e1nh]], did not have their first son for some time. This situation worried the grand chancellor Tr\u1ea7n Th\u1ee7 \u0110\u1ed9 because he had profited from similar circumstances with the Emperor L\u00fd Hu\u1ec7 T\u00f4ng in overthrowing the L\u00fd dynasty. Therefore, in 1237 Tr\u1ea7n Th\u1ee7 \u0110\u1ed9 decided to force Prince Ho\u00e0i [[Tr\u1ea7n Li\u1ec5u]], Th\u00e1i T\u00f4ng's elder brother, to give up his wife, Princess Thu\u1eadn Thi\u00ean, for the Emperor when she had been pregnant with [[Tr\u1ea7n Qu\u1ed1c Khang]] for three months. After the royal marriage, Thu\u1eadn Thi\u00ean was entitled the new empress of the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty, while Chi\u00eau Th\u00e1nh was downgraded to princess. Furious at losing his pregnant wife, Tr\u1ea7n Li\u1ec5u rose in revolt against the royal family. Meanwhile, Th\u00e1i T\u00f4ng felt awkward about the situation and decided to become a monk at [[Y\u00ean T\u1eed Mountain]] in [[Qu\u1ea3ng Ninh]]. Finally Tr\u1ea7n Th\u1ee7 \u0110\u1ed9 successfully persuaded Th\u00e1i T\u00f4ng to return to the throne, and Tr\u1ea7n Li\u1ec5u had to surrender after judging that he could not stand with his fragile force. All soldiers who participated in this revolt were killed; Tr\u1ea7n Th\u1ee7 \u0110\u1ed9 even wanted to behead Tr\u1ea7n Li\u1ec5u but was stopped by Th\u00e1i T\u00f4ng.{{sfn|Tr\u1ea7n Tr\u1ecdng Kim|1971|p=49}}{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|pp=164\u2013166}}{{sfn|National Bureau for Historical Record|1998|pp=195\u2013196}}\n\n[[Fujian]] was the origin of the Tr\u1ea7n ancestors who migrated to Vietnam under Tr\u1ea7n Kinh along with a large amount of other Chinese during the Ly dynasty where they served as officials. Distinctly Chinese last names are found in the Tran and Ly dynasty Imperial exam records.<ref name=\"Woodside1971\">{{cite book|author=Alexander Woodside|title=Vietnam and the Chinese Model: A Comparative Study of Vietnamese and Chinese Government in the First Half of the Nineteenth Century|url=https://books.google.com/?id=0LgSI9UQNpwC&pg=PA8&dq=tran+fukien#v=onepage&q=tran%20fukien&f=false|year=1971|publisher=Harvard Univ Asia Center|isbn=978-0-674-93721-5|pages=8\u2013}}</ref> Ethnic Chinese are recorded in Tran and Ly dynasty records of officials.<ref name=\"Gunn2011\">{{cite book|author=Geoffrey C. Gunn|title=History Without Borders: The Making of an Asian World Region, 1000\u20131800|url=https://books.google.com/?id=E10tnvapZt0C&pg=PA112&dq=tran+fujian#v=onepage&q=tran%20fujian&f=false|date=1 August 2011|publisher=Hong Kong University Press|isbn=978-988-8083-34-3|pages=112\u2013}}</ref> Clothing, food, and language were all Chinese-dominated in [[Van Don]] where the Tran had moved to after leaving their home province of Fujian. The Chinese language could still be spoken by the Tran in Vietnam.<ref name=\"Taylor2013\">{{cite book|author=K. W. Taylor|title=A History of the Vietnamese|url=https://books.google.com/?id=6UHi9JXNokEC&pg=PA120&dq=tran+fujian#v=onepage&q=tran%20fujian&f=false|date=9 May 2013|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-24435-1|pages=120\u2013}}</ref> The oceanside area of Vietnam was colonized by Chinese migrants from Fujian which included the Tran among them located to the capital's southeastern area.<ref name=\"Hall2008\">{{cite book|author=Kenneth R. Hall|title=Secondary Cities and Urban Networking in the Indian Ocean Realm, C. 1400\u20131800|url=https://books.google.com/?id=gyPjBevBHxcC&pg=PA159&dq=tran+fujian#v=onepage&q=tran%20fujian&f=false|year=2008|publisher=Lexington Books|isbn=978-0-7391-2835-0|pages=159\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Hall1955\">{{cite book|author=Hall|title=Secondary Cities & Urban Networking in the Indian Ocean Realm, c. 1400\u20131800|url=https://books.google.com/?id=nZaaAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA159&dq=tran+fujian#v=onepage&q=tran%20fujian&f=false|date=1 January 1955|publisher=Lexington Books|isbn=978-0-7391-3043-8|pages=159\u2013}}</ref> The [[Red River Delta]] was subjected to migration from Fujian including the Tran and Van Don port arose as a result of this interaction.<ref name=\"WernerWhitmore2012\">{{cite book|author1=Jayne Werner|author2=John K. Whitmore|author3=George Dutton|title=Sources of Vietnamese Tradition|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ZHD4Asj0FagC&pg=PT90&dq=Tran+Chen+Fujian#v=onepage&q=Tran%20Chen%20Fujian&f=false|date=21 August 2012|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=978-0-231-51110-0|pages=29\u2013}}</ref> [[Guangdong]] and Fujian Chinese moved to the [[Halong bay|Halong]] located Van Don coastal port during Ly Anh Tong's rule in order to engage in commerce.<ref name=\"Truong2007\">{{cite book|author=Philippe Truong|title=The Elephant and the Lotus: Vietnamese Ceramics in the Museum of Fine Arts, Boston|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ERvrAAAAMAAJ&q=tran+fujian&dq=tran+fujian|year=2007|publisher=MFA Pub.|isbn=978-0-87846-717-4|page=18}}</ref> The usurpation of the Ly occurred after they married with the Fujianese Tran family, many of whom were fishermen.<ref name=\"EmbreeLewis1988\">{{cite book|author1=Ainslie Thomas Embree|author2=Robin Jeanne Lewis|title=Encyclopedia of Asian history|url=https://books.google.com/?id=cNwpAQAAMAAJ&q=tran+fujian&dq=tran+fujian|year=1988|publisher=Scribner|page=190}}</ref>\n\n===Mongol invasions===\n{{see also|Mongol invasions of Vietnam|Tr\u1ea7n Th\u00e1nh T\u00f4ng|Tr\u1ea7n Nh\u00e2n T\u00f4ng}}\n\nIn 1257 the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty successfully fended off the first [[Mongol invasions of Vietnam|Mongol invasion]] of [[\u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t]].{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=173}} At the beginning of the war, the \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t army suffered several defeats by an overwhelming force that had already conquered a vast area in Asia. Several high-ranking officials of the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty were so fearful that Prince Kh\u00e2m Thi\u00ean [[Tr\u1ea7n Nh\u1eadt Hi\u1ec7u]]{{Specify|reason=is this one person? or two?|date=November 2019}}, the younger brother of Th\u00e1i T\u00f4ng, even suggested to the Emperor that they might escape from \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t to the [[Song dynasty]].{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|pp=172\u2013173}} Due to the firm faith of Emperor Th\u00e1i T\u00f4ng, grand chancellor Tr\u1ea7n Th\u1ee7 \u0110\u1ed9, and talented generals such as Prince H\u01b0ng \u0110\u1ea1o [[Tr\u1ea7n Qu\u1ed1c Tu\u1ea5n]] and [[L\u00ea Ph\u1ee5 Tr\u1ea7n]], the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty was able to drive back the invasion and ultimately re-establish the peace in \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t in the twelfth lunar month of 1257.{{sfn|Chapuis|1995|p=81}}{{sfn|Tr\u1ea7n Tr\u1ecdng Kim|1971|p=51}}\n[[File:Viet Royal Battle Standard.JPG|thumb|left|150px|Tr\u1ea7n royal battle standard]]\n[[File:Tran Hung Dao statue.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Statue of noble admiral [[Tr\u1ea7n Qu\u1ed1c Tu\u1ea5n]].]]\n\nIn the twelfth lunar month of 1284, the second Yuan invasion of \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t was launched under the command of Kublai Khan's prince [[Toghon (son of Kublai)|Toghon]].{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|pp=189\u2013190}} \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t was attacked from two directions, with Toghan himself conducting an infantry invasion from the northern border while the Yuan navy under general [[Sogetu]] advanced from the southern border through the territory of [[Champa]].{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=193}} Initially, [[Tr\u1ea7n Th\u00e1nh T\u00f4ng]] and [[Tr\u1ea7n Nh\u00e2n T\u00f4ng]] had to order the army to retreat to avoid the pressure from the Yuan force when Prince Chi\u00eau Minh [[Tr\u1ea7n Quang Kh\u1ea3i]] commanded his troops to try to stop Sogetu's fleet in the province of [[Ngh\u1ec7 An]]. Meanwhile, several high-ranking officials and members of the royal family of the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty defected to the Yuan side, including Th\u00e1nh T\u00f4ng's own brother, Prince Chi\u00eau Qu\u1ed1c ([[Tr\u1ea7n \u00cdch T\u1eafc]]) and Tr\u1ea7n Ki\u1ec7n, who was the son of Prince T\u0129nh Qu\u1ed1c ([[Tr\u1ea7n Qu\u1ed1c Khang]]). To ensure the safety of Th\u00e1nh T\u00f4ng and Nh\u00e2n T\u00f4ng during their retreat, Princess [[An T\u01b0]] was offered as a present and diversion for prince Toghan, while Marquis B\u1ea3o Ngh\u0129a ([[Tr\u1ea7n B\u00ecnh Tr\u1ecdng]]) was captured and later killed in the [[Battle of \u0110\u00e0 M\u1ea1c]] defending the two emperors.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=192}} At the southern border, Tr\u1ea7n Quang Kh\u1ea3i also had to retreat under the pressure of Sogetu's navy and the defection of the governor of Nghe An.{{sfn|Chapuis|1995|p=83}} This critical situation for the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty began to change after their victory in the fourth lunar month of 1285 at the [[Battle of H\u00e0m T\u1eed]], where the troops commanded by [[Tr\u1ea7n Nh\u1eadt Du\u1eadt]], Prince Chi\u00eau Th\u00e0nh, [[Tr\u1ea7n Qu\u1ed1c To\u1ea3n]], and [[Nguy\u1ec5n Kho\u00e1i]] were finally able to defeat the fleet of general Sogetu. On the tenth day of the fifth lunar month of 1285, Tr\u1ea7n Quang Kh\u1ea3i fought the decisive battle in the [[Battle of Ch\u01b0\u01a1ng D\u01b0\u01a1ng|Ch\u01b0\u01a1ng D\u01b0\u01a1ng]], where the Yuan navy was almost destroyed and the balance in the battlefield tilted definitively in favor of the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty.{{sfn|Chapuis|1995|p=83}}{{sfn|Tr\u1ea7n Tr\u1ecdng Kim|1971|p=58}} Ten days later Sogetu was killed and the Tr\u1ea7n Emperor Nh\u00e2n T\u00f4ng and Emperor Emeritus Th\u00e1nh T\u00f4ng returned to the capital, Th\u0103ng Long, on the sixth day of the sixth lunar month, 1285.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|pp=192\u2013195}}\n\nIn the third lunar month of 1287, the [[Yuan dynasty]] launched their third invasion of \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=195}} This time, unlike the second invasion, commander-in-chief Prince H\u01b0ng \u0110\u1ea1o (Tr\u1ea7n Qu\u1ed1c Tu\u1ea5n) assured the Emperor that \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t's army could easily break the Yuan military campaign. This invasion was indeed ended one year later by a disastrous defeat of the Yuan navy at the [[Battle of B\u1ea1ch \u0110\u1eb1ng (1288)|Battle of B\u1ea1ch \u0110\u1eb1ng]] on the eighth day of the third lunar month, 1288.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|pp=196\u2013198}} Besides Tr\u1ea7n Qu\u1ed1c Tu\u1ea5n, other notable generals of the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty during this time were Prince Nh\u00e2n Hu\u1ec7 [[Tr\u1ea7n Kh\u00e1nh D\u01b0]], who destroyed the logistics convoy of the Yuan navy{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=197}}{{sfn|Tr\u1ea7n Tr\u1ecdng Kim|1971|p=61}}{{sfn|Chapuis|1995|p=84}}<ref>{{cite book|title=Khubilai Khan's Lost Fleet: In Search of a Legendary Armada|pages=161\u2013162|first=James P.|last= Delgado|publisher=University of California Press|year=2009|isbn=978-0-520-25976-8}}</ref> at the [[Battle of V\u00e2n \u0110\u1ed3n]], and general [[Ph\u1ea1m Ng\u0169 L\u00e3o]], who took charge of ambushing prince Toghan's retreating troops.{{sfn|Tr\u1ea7n Tr\u1ecdng Kim|1971|p=62}}\n\nProfessor Liam Kelley noted that people from Song dynasty China, like Zhao Zhong and [[Xu Zongdao]] fled to Tran dynasty, ruled Vietnam after the Mongol invasion of the Song and they helped the Tran fight against the Mongol invasion. Like the Tran dynasty, the [[Daoist]] cleric Xu Zongdao originated from Fujian. He recorded the Mongol invasion and referred to the Mongols as \"Northern bandits\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://leminhkhai.wordpress.com/2015/12/04/giac-bac-den-xam-luoc-translations-and-exclamation-points/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-03 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006151416/https://leminhkhai.wordpress.com/2015/12/04/giac-bac-den-xam-luoc-translations-and-exclamation-points/ |archivedate=2016-10-06 }}</ref><ref name=\"proof that he runs the blog\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20141014090118/http://manoa.hawaii.edu/history/node/44 proof that he runs the blog]</ref>\n\n[[Wu Bozong]] [[w:zh:\u5433\u4f2f\u5b97|\u5433\u4f2f\u5b97]] (b. 1334-d. 1384) was sent as ambassador to Annam. Wu wrote in the [[Rongjinji]] \u69ae\u9032\u96c6 that when he asked the Tran monarch about Annam's affairs, the Tran ruler said that Annam proudly adhered to [[Tang dynasty]] and [[Han dynasty]] customs.\n\n<blockquote>\n\u6b32\u554f\u5b89\u5357\u4e8b\uff0c<br>\u5b89\u5357\u98a8\u4fd7\u6df3\u3002<br>\u8863\u51a0\u5510\u5236\u5ea6\uff0c<br>\u79ae\u6a02\u6f22\u541b\u81e3\u3002<br>\u7389\u7515\u958b\u65b0\u9152\uff0c<br>\u91d1\u5200\u65ab\u7d30\u9c57\u3002<br>\u5e74\u5e74\u4e8c\u4e09\u6708\uff0c<br>\u6843\u674e\u4e00\u822c\u6625\u3002{{Citation needed|date=June 2019|reason=I'm guessing it's from the Rongjinji, but an official citation with page numbers (if applicable) would be helpful; maybe the Chinese wiki has citations?}}<br>\n</blockquote>\n\n===Peace and southward expansion (into Champa)===\n{{see also|Tr\u1ea7n Anh T\u00f4ng|Tr\u1ea7n Minh T\u00f4ng}}\n[[File:VN_lancer.jpg|left|250px|thumb|Terracotta depiction Tr\u1ea7n-era [[soldiers]] and [[lancer]].]]\n\nAfter the three invasions, the people of \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t were finally able to enjoy a long period of prosperity and peace during the reigns of [[Tr\u1ea7n Anh T\u00f4ng]], [[Tr\u1ea7n Minh T\u00f4ng]], and [[Tr\u1ea7n Hi\u1ebfn T\u00f4ng]].{{sfn|Tr\u1ea7n Tr\u1ecdng Kim|1971|p=65}}{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=205}} Anh T\u00f4ng was the first Tr\u1ea7n emperor to reign without facing attacks from the [[Mongol Empire]]. Despite the deaths of the two most important generals of the early Tr\u1ea7n dynasty, [[Tr\u1ea7n Quang Kh\u1ea3i]] in 1294 and [[Tr\u1ea7n Qu\u1ed1c Tu\u1ea5n]] in 1300, the Emperor was still served by many efficient [[Mandarin (bureaucrat)|mandarins]] like Tr\u1ea7n Nh\u1eadt Du\u1eadt, [[\u0110o\u00e0n Nh\u1eef H\u00e0i]], Ph\u1ea1m Ng\u0169 L\u00e3o, [[Tr\u01b0\u01a1ng H\u00e1n Si\u00eau]], [[M\u1ea1c \u0110\u0129nh Chi]], and [[Nguy\u1ec5n Trung Ng\u1ea1n]]. Anh T\u00f4ng was very strict in suppressing gambling and corruption, but he also generously rewarded those who served him well.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=207}}\n\nIn 1306, the king of [[Champa]], [[Ch\u1ebf M\u00e2n]], offered Vietnam two Cham prefectures, \u00d4 and L\u00fd, in exchange for a marriage with the Vietnamese princess [[Huy\u1ec1n Tr\u00e2n]].{{sfn|Chapuis|1995|p=85}} Anh T\u00f4ng accepted this offer, then took and renamed \u00d4 prefecture and L\u00fd prefecture to Thu\u1eadn prefecture and H\u00f3a prefecture. These two prefectures soon began to be referred to collectively as the [[Thu\u1eadn H\u00f3a]] region.{{sfn|Chapuis|1995|p=85}} Only one year into the marriage, Ch\u1ebf M\u00e2n died and, in line with the royal tradition of Champa, Huy\u1ec1n Tr\u00e2n was to be [[Sati (practice)|cremated with her husband]]. Facing this urgent condition, Anh T\u00f4ng sent his mandarin [[Tr\u1ea7n Kh\u1eafc Chung]] to Champa to save Huy\u1ec1n Tr\u00e2n from an imminent death. Finally Huy\u1ec1n Tr\u00e2n was able to return to \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t, but [[Ch\u1ebf Ch\u00ed]], the successor of Ch\u1ebf M\u00e2n, no longer wished to abide by the peace treaty with \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t. After that event, Anh T\u00f4ng himself, along with the generals [[Tr\u1ea7n Qu\u1ed1c Ch\u00e2n]] and Tr\u1ea7n Kh\u00e1nh D\u01b0, commanded three groups of \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t military units to attack Champa in 1312. Ch\u1ebf Ch\u00ed was defeated and captured in this invasion,{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=223}} and Anh T\u00f4ng installed a hand-picked successor, but the relations between \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t and Champa remained strained{{Specify|reason=So was Champa a Tran protectorate? Or were they separate rivaling states? How was it 'strained'?|date=November 2019}} for a long time afterwards.{{sfn|Tr\u1ea7n Tr\u1ecdng Kim|1971|p=66}}{{sfn|Chapuis|1995|p=86}}\n\n===Decline===\n{{see also|Tr\u1ea7n D\u1ee5 T\u00f4ng|Tr\u1ea7n Ngh\u1ec7 T\u00f4ng|D\u01b0\u01a1ng Nh\u1eadt L\u1ec5}}\nAfter the death of the Retired Emperor [[Tr\u1ea7n Minh T\u00f4ng]] in 1357, the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty began to fall into chaos during the reign of [[Tr\u1ea7n D\u1ee5 T\u00f4ng]]. While being modest and diligent under the regency of Minh T\u00f4ng, the reign of Emperor D\u1ee5 T\u00f4ng saw extravagant spending on the building of several luxurious palaces and other indulgences.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|pp=258\u2013259}}{{sfn|Tr\u1ea7n Tr\u1ecdng Kim|1971|p=69}} D\u1ee5 T\u00f4ng introduced theatre, which was considered at the time to be a shameful pleasure, into the royal court.{{sfn|Chapuis|1995|p=89}} The Emperor died on the 25th day of the fifth lunar month, 1369, at the age of 28, after appointing<!--Who appointed his brother's son?--> his brother's son [[D\u01b0\u01a1ng Nh\u1eadt L\u1ec5]] despite the fact that his appointee was not from the Tr\u1ea7n clan.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=259}}\n\nLike his predecessor D\u1ee5 T\u00f4ng, Nh\u1eadt L\u1ec5 neglected his administrative duties and concentrated only on drinking, theatre, and wandering. He even wanted to change his family name back to D\u01b0\u01a1ng. Such activities disappointed everyone in the royal court. This prompted the Prime Minister [[Tr\u1ea7n Nguy\u00ean Tr\u00e1c]] and his son Tr\u1ea7n Nguy\u00ean Ti\u1ebft to plot the assassination of Nh\u1eadt L\u1ec5, but their conspiracy was discovered by the Emperor and they were killed afterwards. In the tenth lunar month of 1370, the Emperor's father-in-law, [[Tr\u1ea7n Ph\u1ee7]], after receiving advice from several mandarins and members of the royal family, decided to raise an army for the purpose of overthrowing Nh\u1eadt L\u1ec5. After one month, his plan succeeded and Tr\u1ea7n Ph\u1ee7 became the new emperor of \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t, ruling as Tr\u1ea7n Ngh\u1ec7 T\u00f4ng, while Nh\u1eadt L\u1ec5 was downgraded to Duke of H\u00f4n \u0110\u1ee9c (H\u00f4n \u0110\u1ee9c C\u00f4ng) and was killed afterwards by an order of Ngh\u1ec7 T\u00f4ng.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|pp=262\u2013263}}<ref name=KDVS292>{{Harvnb|National Bureau for Historical Record|1998|p=292}}</ref>{{sfn|Chapuis|1995|pp=89\u201390}}{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=250}}\n\nAfter the death of H\u00f4n \u0110\u1ee9c C\u00f4ng, his mother fled to [[Champa]] and begged King [[Ch\u1ebf B\u1ed3ng Nga]] to attack \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t. Taking advantage of his neighbour's lack of political stability, Ch\u1ebf B\u1ed3ng Nga commanded troops and directly assaulted [[Hanoi|Th\u0103ng Long]], the capital of \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t. The Tr\u1ea7n army could not withstand this attack and the Tr\u1ea7n royal court had to escape from Th\u0103ng Long, creating an opportunity for Ch\u1ebf B\u1ed3ng Nga to violently loot the capital before withdrawing.{{sfn|Tr\u1ea7n Tr\u1ecdng Kim|1971|p=70}} In the twelfth lunar month of 1376 the Emperor [[Tr\u1ea7n Du\u1ec7 T\u00f4ng]] decided to personally command a military campaign against Champa. Eventually, the campaign was ended by a disastrous defeat of \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t's army at the [[Battle of \u0110\u1ed3 B\u00e0n]], when the Emperor himself, along with many high-ranking madarins and generals of the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty, were killed by the Cham forces.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|pp=269\u2013270}} The successor of Du\u1ec7 T\u00f4ng, [[Tr\u1ea7n Ph\u1ebf \u0110\u1ebf]], and the retired Emperor Ngh\u1ec7 T\u00f4ng, were unable to drive back any invasion of Ch\u1ebf B\u1ed3ng Nga in \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t. As a result, Ngh\u1ec7 T\u00f4ng even decided to hide money in [[L\u1ea1ng S\u01a1n]], fearing that Ch\u1ebf B\u1ed3ng Nga's troops might assault and destroy the royal palace in Th\u0103ng Long.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=273}}{{sfn|Chapuis|1995|p=91}} In 1389 general [[Tr\u1ea7n Kh\u00e1t Ch\u00e2n]] was appointed by Ngh\u1ec7 T\u00f4ng to take charge of stopping Champa.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=281}} In the first lunar month of 1390, Tr\u1ea7n Kh\u00e1t Ch\u00e2n had a decisive victory over Champa which resulted in the death of Ch\u1ebf B\u1ed3ng Nga and stabilised situation in the southern part of \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4|1993|pp=282\u2013283}}\n\n===Downfall===\n{{see also|H\u1ed3 Qu\u00fd Ly|Tr\u1ea7n Thu\u1eadn T\u00f4ng}}\nDuring the reign of Tr\u1ea7n Ngh\u1ec7 T\u00f4ng, [[H\u1ed3 Qu\u00fd Ly]], an official who had two aunts entitled as consorts of Minh T\u00f4ng,{{sfn|Chapuis|1995|p=90}} was appointed to one of the highest positions in the royal court. Despite his complicity in the death of the Emperor Du\u1ec7 T\u00f4ng, H\u1ed3 Qu\u00fd Ly still had Ngh\u1ec7 T\u00f4ng's confidence and came to hold more and more power in royal court.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=270}} Facing the unstoppable rise of H\u1ed3 Qu\u00fd Ly in the court, the Emperor Tr\u1ea7n Ph\u1ebf \u0110\u1ebf plotted with minister [[Tr\u1ea7n Ng\u1ea1c]] to reduce H\u1ed3 Qu\u00fd Ly's power, but H\u1ed3 Qu\u00fd Ly pre-empted this plot by a defamation campaign against the Emperor which ultimately made Ngh\u1ec7 T\u00f4ng decide to replace him by [[Tr\u1ea7n Thu\u1eadn T\u00f4ng]] and downgrade Ph\u1ebf \u0110\u1ebf to Prince Linh \u0110\u1ee9c in December 1388.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|pp=278\u2013279}}{{sfn|Chapuis|1995|p=94}} Tr\u1ea7n Ngh\u1ec7 T\u00f4ng died on the 15th day of the twelfth lunar month, 1394 at the age of 73 leaving the royal court in the total control of H\u1ed3 Qu\u00fd Ly.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4|1993|pp=287\u2013288}} He began to reform the administrative and examination systems of the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty and eventually obliged Thu\u1eadn T\u00f4ng to change the capital from Th\u0103ng Long to [[Thanh H\u00f3a]] in January 1397.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4|1993|pp=288\u2013291}}\n\nOn the full moon of the third lunar month, 1398, under pressure from H\u1ed3 Qu\u00fd Ly, Thu\u1eadn T\u00f4ng, had to cede the throne to his three-year-old son [[Tr\u1ea7n An]], now [[Tr\u1ea7n Thi\u1ebfu \u0110\u1ebf]], and held the title Retired Emperor at the age of only 20.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=292}} Only one year after his resignation, Thu\u1eadn T\u00f4ng was killed on the orders of H\u1ed3 Qu\u00fd Ly.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=294}} H\u1ed3 Qu\u00fd Ly also authorised the execution of over 370 persons who opposed his dominance in the royal court, including several prominent mandarins and the Emperor's relatives together with their families, such as Tr\u1ea7n Kh\u00e1t Ch\u00e2n, [[Tr\u1ea7n H\u00e3ng]], [[Ph\u1ea1m Kh\u1ea3 V\u0129nh]] and [[L\u01b0\u01a1ng Nguy\u00ean B\u01b0u]].{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|pp=294\u2013295}} The end of the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty came on the 28th day of the second lunar month (Gregorian: March 23) 1400, when H\u1ed3 Qu\u00fd Ly decided to overthrow Thi\u1ebfu \u0110\u1ebf and established a new dynasty, the [[H\u1ed3 dynasty]].{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=296}} Being H\u1ed3 Qu\u00fd Ly's own grandson, Thi\u1ebfu \u0110\u1ebf was downgraded to Prince B\u1ea3o Ninh instead of being killed like his father.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=296}}{{sfn|Chapuis|1995|p=96}} H\u1ed3 Qu\u00fd Ly claimed descent from [[Duke Hu of Chen]] (Tr\u1ea7n H\u1ed3 c\u00f4ng, \u9673\u80e1\u516c), whose H\u1ed3 clan originated in [[Chen (state)|State of Chen]] (modern day [[Zhejiang]], China<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=P2HP31kOSA4C&pg=PA166#v=onepage&q&f=false Taylor 2013] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161125082245/https://books.google.com/books?id=P2HP31kOSA4C&pg=PA166#v=onepage&q&f=false|date=November 25, 2016}}, p. 166.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=gyPjBevBHxcC&pg=PA161#v=onepage&q&f=false ed. Hall 2008] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161125125852/https://books.google.com/books?id=gyPjBevBHxcC&pg=PA161#v=onepage&q&f=false|date=November 25, 2016}}, p. 161.</ref>) around the 940s.\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:Tien-giay-co.jpg|200px|thumb|right|\u201cH\u1ed9i sao th\u00f4ng b\u1ea3o\u201d\u2014the earliest banknote of Vietnam, printed in 1396.]]\nTo restore the country's economy, which had been heavily damaged during the turbulent time at the end of the L\u00fd dynasty, Emperor Tr\u1ea7n Th\u00e1i T\u00f4ng decided to reform the nation's system of taxation by introducing a new personal tax (''thu\u1ebf th\u00e2n''), which was levied on each person according to the area of cultivated land owned.{{sfn|Chapuis|1998|p=80}} For example, a farmer who owned one or two ''m\u1eabu'', equal to {{convert|3600|to|7200|m2|sqft}}, had to pay one ''quan'' per year, while another with up to four ''m\u1eabus'' had to pay two ''quan''. Besides personal taxes, farmers were obliged to pay a land tax in measures of rice that was calculated by land classification. One historical book reveals that the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty taxed everything from fish and fruits to [[betel]].{{sfn|Tr\u1ea7n Tr\u1ecdng Kim|1971|p=50}} Taxpayers were divided into three categories: minors (''ti\u1ec3u ho\u00e0ng nam'', from 18 to 20), adults (''\u0111\u1ea1i ho\u00e0ng nam'', from 20 to 60), and seniors (''l\u00e3o h\u1ea1ng'', over 60).{{sfn|Chapuis|1998|p=80}}{{sfn|Tr\u1ea7n Tr\u1ecdng Kim|1971|p=50}} During the reign of Tr\u1ea7n Th\u00e1nh T\u00f4ng members of the Tr\u1ea7n clan and royal family were required by the Emperor to take full advantage of their land grants by hiring the poor to cultivate them.{{sfn|Chapuis|1998|p=81}} {{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=179}} \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t's cultivated land was annually ruined by river floods, so for a more stable agriculture, in 1244 Tr\u1ea7n Th\u00e1i T\u00f4ng ordered his subordinates to construct a new system of [[levee]]s along the [[Red River (Asia)|Red River]]. Farmers who had to sacrifice their land for the diking were compensated with the value of the land. The Emperor also appointed a separate official to control the system.{{sfn|Tr\u1ea7n Tr\u1ecdng Kim|1971|p=50}}\n\nTowards the end of the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty, H\u1ed3 Qu\u00fd Ly held absolute power in the royal court, and he began to carry out his ideas for reforming the economy of \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t. The most significant change during this time was the replacement of copper coins with [[paper money]] in 1396. It was the first time in the history of Vietnam that paper money was used in trading.{{sfn|Chapuis|1998|p=95}}{{sfn|Tr\u1ea7n Tr\u1ecdng Kim|1971|p=73}}\n\n==Culture==\n\n===Literature===\n[[File:Vietsuluoc.jpg|thumb|right|(\u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t s\u1eed l\u01b0\u1ee3c) History of Vietnam record .]]\n[[File:\u5dba\u5357\u646d\u602a\u5217\u50b3.jpg|thumb|left|L\u0129nh Nam ch\u00edch qu\u00e1i,14th-century Vietnamese historical work written in Han scripts by [[Tr\u1ea7n Th\u1ebf Ph\u00e1p]].]]\n[[File:CuaPhoMinh.jpg|thumb|left|Wooden gate of Ph\u1ed5 Minh pagoda.]]\n\n[[File:ThapGom.jpg|thumb|left|Terracotta Tower]]\nTr\u1ea7n literature is considered superior to L\u00fd literature in both quality and quantity.<!--by whom?-->{{sfn|D\u01b0\u01a1ng Qu\u1ea3ng H\u00e0m|1968|pp=232\u2013238}} Initially, most members of the Tr\u1ea7n clan were fishermen{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=153}} without any depth of knowledge. For example, Tr\u1ea7n Th\u1ee7 \u0110\u1ed9, the founder of the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty, was assessed in ''\u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t s\u1eed k\u00fd to\u00e0n th\u01b0'' as a man of superficial learning.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=178}} However, after their usurpation of power from the L\u00fd dynasty, Tr\u1ea7n emperors and other princes and marquises always attached special importance to culture, especially literature.{{sfn|Tr\u1ea7n Tr\u1ecdng Kim|1971|p=53}}\n\nTwo important schools of literature during the reign of the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty were patriotic and [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] literature. To commemorate the victory of \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t against the second Mongol invasion the grand chancellor Tr\u1ea7n Quang Kh\u1ea3i composed a poem, named ''T\u1ee5ng gi\u00e1 ho\u00e0n kinh'' (''Return to the capital''), which was considered one of the finest examples of Vietnamese patriotic literature during the dynastic era.{{sfn|Tham Seong Chee|1981|pp=304\u2013305}} Patriotism in Tr\u1ea7n literature was also represented by the proclamation ''[[H\u1ecbch t\u01b0\u1edbng s\u0129]]'' (''Call of Soldiers''), written by general Tr\u1ea7n Qu\u1ed1c Tu\u1ea5n, which was the most popular work of the ''h\u1ecbch'' (appeal, call) form in Vietnamese literature.{{sfn|Tham Seong Chee|1981|p=305}}\n\nBesides members of the Tr\u1ea7n clan, there were several mandarins and scholars who were well known for patriotic works such as [[Tr\u01b0\u01a1ng H\u00e1n Si\u00eau]], an eminent author of the ''ph\u00fa'' form,{{sfn|Tr\u1ea7n Tr\u1ecdng Kim|1971|p=53}}{{sfn|Tham Seong Chee|1981|pp=312\u2013313}} or general [[Ph\u1ea1m Ng\u0169 L\u00e3o]] with his famous poem ''Thu\u1eadt ho\u00e0i''. As Buddhism was ''de facto'' the national religion of the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty, there were many works of Tr\u1ea7n literature that expressed the spirit of Buddhism and [[Zen]], notably the works of the Emperor Tr\u1ea7n Nh\u00e2n T\u00f4ng and other masters of Tr\u00fac L\u00e2m School.<ref name=\"lemanhthat\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thuvienhoasen.org/tsncph11-09.htm |title=A Complete Collection of Tr\u1ea7n Nh\u00e2n T\u00f4ng's Works |author=L\u00ea M\u1ea1nh Th\u00e1t |publisher=Thuvienhoasen.org |accessdate=2009-12-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202051948/http://www.thuvienhoasen.org/tsncph11-09.htm |archivedate=December 2, 2008 }}</ref> Besides the literature created by the upper classes, folk narratives of myths, legends, and ghost stories were also collected in ''[[Vi\u1ec7t \u0110i\u1ec7n U Linh T\u1eadp]]'' by [[L\u00fd T\u1ebf Xuy\u00ean]] and ''[[L\u0129nh Nam ch\u00edch qu\u00e1i]]'' by [[Tr\u1ea7n Th\u1ebf Ph\u00e1p]]. These two collections held great value not only for [[folklore|folk]] culture but also for the early history of Vietnam.<ref>{{cite book|pages=14\u201328|title=Cult, culture, and authority: Princess Li\u1ec5u H\u1ea1nh in Vietnamese history|first=Olga|last=Dror|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|year=1997|isbn=0-8248-2972-7}}</ref>\n\nTr\u1ea7n literature had a special role in the history of Vietnamese literature for its introduction and development of the [[Vietnamese language]] (Qu\u1ed1c ng\u1eef) written in [[ch\u1eef n\u00f4m]]. Before the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty, Vietnamese was only used in oral history or proverbs.{{sfn|D\u01b0\u01a1ng Qu\u1ea3ng H\u00e0m|1968|p=292}} Under the rule of the Emperor Tr\u1ea7n Nh\u00e2n T\u00f4ng, it was used for the first time as the second language in official scripts of the royal court, besides [[Chinese language|Chinese]].<ref name=\"lemanhthat\" />\n\nIt was [[H\u00e0n Thuy\u00ean]], an official of Nh\u00e2n T\u00f4ng, who began to compose his literary works in the Vietnamese language, with the earliest recorded poem written in [[ch\u1eef N\u00f4m]] in 1282.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|title=Mountain river: Vietnamese poetry from the wars, 1948\u20131993 : a bilingual collection|pages=xxiv|author1=Kevin Bowen |author2=Ba Chung Nguyen |author3=Bruce Weigl |publisher=Univ of Massachusetts Press|year=1998|isbn=1-55849-141-4}}</ref> He was considered the pioneer who introduced ch\u1eef n\u00f4m in literature.<ref name=\"hanthuyen\">{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.bachkhoatoanthu.gov.vn/default.aspx?param=1F6CaWQ9MjQzMzcmZ3JvdXBpZD0ma2luZD0ma2V5d29yZD1HVVklZTElYmIlODROJTIwVEhVWSVjMyU4YU4=&page=1|title=H\u00e0n Thuy\u00ean|work=[[T\u1eeb \u0111i\u1ec3n B\u00e1ch khoa to\u00e0n th\u01b0 Vi\u1ec7t Nam]]|language=Vietnamese|accessdate=2009-12-10|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716022039/http://dictionary.bachkhoatoanthu.gov.vn/default.aspx?param=1F6CaWQ9MjQzMzcmZ3JvdXBpZD0ma2luZD0ma2V5d29yZD1HVVklZTElYmIlODROJTIwVEhVWSVjMyU4YU4=&page=1|archivedate=2011-07-16}}</ref> After H\u00e0n Thuy\u00ean, ch\u1eef N\u00f4m was progressively used by Tr\u1ea7n scholars in composing Vietnamese literature, such as [[Chu V\u0103n An]] with the collection ''Qu\u1ed1c ng\u1eef thi t\u1eadp'' (''Collection of national language poems'') or H\u1ed3 Qu\u00fd Ly who wrote ''Qu\u1ed1c ng\u1eef thi ngh\u0129a'' to explain ''[[Shi Jing]]'' in the Vietnamese language.{{sfn|D\u01b0\u01a1ng Qu\u1ea3ng H\u00e0m|1968|p=294}} The achievement of Vietnamese language literature during the Tr\u1ea7n era was the essential basis for the development of this language and the subsequent literature of Vietnam.<ref name=\"lemanhthat\" />\n\n===Performing arts===\n[[File:Binh Son tower 2.jpg|left|150px|thumb|B\u00ecnh S\u01a1n tower in V\u0129nh Kh\u00e1nh pagoda during Tr\u1ea7n dynasty, Tam S\u01a1n town, L\u00f4 river commune, [[V\u0129nh Ph\u00fac province]].]]\n[[File:National Museum Vietnamese History 62.jpg|right|150px|thumb|Phoenix head. Terracotta, Tr\u1ea7n-H\u1ed3 dynasty, 14th\u201315th century. Architectural decoration. National Museum of Vietnamese History, Hanoi.]] \n[[File:National Museum Vietnamese History 64.jpg|left|150px|thumb| Lion figure. Terracotta, Tr\u1ea7n-H\u1ed3 dynasty, 14th\u201315th century. Ngh\u1ec7 An province, central Vietnam. Architectural decoration. National Museum of Vietnamese History, Hanoi.]]\n[[File:National Museum Vietnamese History 35.jpg|right|150px|thumb|The boy Buddha rising up from lotus. Crimson and gilded wood, Tr\u1ea7n-H\u1ed3 dynasty, 14th\u201315th century. Statue for worship. National Museum of Vietnamese History, Hanoi.]]\n\nThe Tr\u1ea7n dynasty was considered a golden age for music and culture.{{sfn|Terry E. Miller, Sean Williams|2008|p=249}} Although it was still seen as a shameful pleasure at that time, theatre rapidly developed towards the end of the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty with the role of [[L\u00fd Nguy\u00ean C\u00e1t]] (Li Yuan Ki), a captured Chinese soldier who was granted a pardon for his talent in theatre. L\u00fd Nguy\u00ean C\u00e1t imported many features of [[Beijing opera|Chinese theatre]] (also see \u8bdd\u5267) in the performing arts of \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t such as stories, costumes, roles, and acrobatics.{{sfn|Terry E. Miller, Sean Williams|2008|p=249}} For that reason, L\u00fd Nguy\u00ean C\u00e1t was traditionally considered the founder of the art of ''[[h\u00e1t tu\u1ed3ng]]'' in Vietnam. However this is nowadays a challenged hypothesis because ''h\u00e1t tu\u1ed3ng'' and Beijing opera differed in the way of using painted faces, costumes, or theatrical conventions.{{sfn|Terry E. Miller, Sean Williams|2008|p=274}} The art of theatre was introduced to the royal court by Tr\u1ea7n D\u1ee5 T\u00f4ng and eventually the emperor even decided to cede the throne to D\u01b0\u01a1ng Nh\u1eadt L\u1ec5 who was born to a couple of ''h\u00e1t tu\u1ed3ng'' performers.{{sfn|Chapuis|1995|p=89}}\n\nTo celebrate the victory over the 1288 Mongol invasion, Tr\u1ea7n Quang Kh\u1ea3i and Tr\u1ea7n Nh\u1eadt Du\u1eadt created the ''[[M\u00faa b\u00e0i b\u00f4ng]]'' (''dance of flowers'') for a major three-day festival in Th\u0103ng Long.<!--What was the festival called?--> This dance has been handed down to the present and is still performed at local festivals in the northern region.{{sfn|Terry E. Miller, Sean Williams|2008|pp=278\u2013279}}\n\n==Education and imperial examination system==\n[[File:National Museum Vietnamese History 32.jpg|thumb|Carved wooden doors from the Ph\u1ed5 Minh pagoda, Nam \u0110\u1ecbnh province, northern Vietnam (13th\u201314th century)]]\n[[File:Bronze ceremonial helmet from the Tran Dynasty in Dai-Viet (modern-day Vietnam) circa 12th - 13th century.JPG|thumb|Bronze ceremonial helmet from the Tran dynasty in Dai-Viet]]\n[[File:Chu V\u0103n An.jpg|thumb|left|Statue of noble professor [[Chu V\u0103n An]] who was the royal professor of Tran dynasty in Dai-Viet]]\n[[File:T\u01b0\u1ee3ng M\u1ea1c \u0110\u0129nh Chi.jpeg|thumb|left|Statue of noble scholar [[M\u1ea1c \u0110\u0129nh Chi]] of Tran dynasty who was the ancestor of emperor [[M\u1ea1c \u0110\u0103ng Dung]]. ]]\n\nAlthough [[Buddhism]] was considered the [[State religion|national religion]] of the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty, [[Confucianist]] education began to spread across the country. The principal curricula during this time were the [[Four Books and Five Classics]], and [[History of China|Northern history]], which were at the beginning taught only at Buddhist pagodas and gradually brought to pupils in private classes organized by retired officials or Confucian scholars.{{sfn|Tr\u01b0\u01a1ng H\u1eefu Qu\u00fdnh, \u0110inh Xu\u00e2n L\u00e2m, L\u00ea M\u1eadu H\u00e3n|2008|p=261}} The most famous teacher of the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty was probably [[Chu V\u0103n An]], an official in the royal court from the reign of Tr\u1ea7n Minh T\u00f4ng to the reign of Tr\u1ea7n D\u1ee5 T\u00f4ng, who also served as royal professor of Crown Prince [[Tr\u1ea7n V\u01b0\u1ee3ng]].{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|p=263}} During the reign of Tr\u1ea7n Th\u00e1nh T\u00f4ng, the emperor also permitted his brother [[Tr\u1ea7n \u00cdch T\u1eafc]], a prince who was well known for his intelligence and knowledge, to open his own school at the prince's palace.{{sfn|Chapuis|1998|p=81}} Several prominent mandarins of the future royal court such as [[M\u1ea1c \u0110\u0129nh Chi]] and [[B\u00f9i Ph\u00f3ng]] were trained at this school.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=180}} The official school of the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty, Qu\u1ed1c h\u1ecdc vi\u1ec7n, was established in June 1253 to teach the [[Four Books and Five Classics]] to royal students (''th\u00e1i h\u1ecdc sinh''). The military school, Gi\u1ea3ng v\u00f5 \u0111\u01b0\u1eddng, which focused on teaching about war and military manoeuvre, was opened in August of the same year.{{sfn|Tr\u1ea7n Tr\u1ecdng Kim|1971|p=50}}{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=171}} Together with this military school, the first Temple of Military Men (V\u00f5 mi\u1ebfu) was built in Th\u0103ng Long to worship [[Jiang Ziya]] and other famous generals.<ref>{{cite book|title=Opusculum de sectis apud Sinenses et Tunkinenses: A small treatise on the sects among the Chinese and Tonkinese|year=2002|pages=128|author=Adriano (di St. Thecla), Olga Dror|others=Olga Dror (trans.)|publisher=SEAP Publications|isbn=0-87727-732-X}}</ref>\n\nSeven years after the establishment of the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty, the Emperor [[Tr\u1ea7n Th\u00e1i T\u00f4ng]] ordered the first [[imperial examination]], in the second lunar month of 1232, for royal students with the purpose of choosing the best scholars in [[\u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t]] for numerous high-ranking positions in the royal court. Two of the top candidates in this examination were [[Tr\u01b0\u01a1ng Hanh]] and [[L\u01b0u Di\u1ec5m]].{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=163}} After another imperial examination in 1239, the Tr\u1ea7n emperor began to establish the system of seven-year periodic examinations in order to select royal students from all over the country.{{sfn|Tr\u01b0\u01a1ng H\u1eefu Qu\u00fdnh, \u0110inh Xu\u00e2n L\u00e2m, L\u00ea M\u1eadu H\u00e3n|2008|p=261}} The most prestigious title of this examination was ''tam kh\u00f4i'' (''three first laureates''), which was composed of three candidates who ranked first, second, and third in the examination with the names respectively of ''tr\u1ea1ng nguy\u00ean'' ([[wikt:\u72c0|\u72c0]] [[wikt:\u5143|\u5143]], ''exemplar of the state''), ''b\u1ea3ng nh\u00e3n'' ([[wikt:\u699c|\u699c]] [[wikt:\u773c|\u773c]], ''eyes positioned alongside'') and ''th\u00e1m hoa'' ([[wikt:\u63a2|\u63a2]] [[wikt:\u82b1|\u82b1]], ''selective talent'').{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|pp=168\u2013169}} The first ''tam kh\u00f4i'' of the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty were ''tr\u1ea1ng nguy\u00ean'' [[Nguy\u1ec5n Hi\u1ec1n]], who was only 12 at that time,<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|url=http://dictionary.bachkhoatoanthu.gov.vn/default.aspx?param=1EC7aWQ9MjIwODImZ3JvdXBpZD0ma2luZD0ma2V5d29yZD1OZ3V5JWUxJWJiJTg1bitIaSVlMSViYiU4MW4=&page=1|title=Nguy\u1ec5n Hi\u1ec1n|language=Vietnamese|encyclopedia=[[T\u1eeb \u0111i\u1ec3n B\u00e1ch khoa to\u00e0n th\u01b0 Vi\u1ec7t Nam]]|accessdate=2009-12-09|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716021953/http://dictionary.bachkhoatoanthu.gov.vn/default.aspx?param=1EC7aWQ9MjIwODImZ3JvdXBpZD0ma2luZD0ma2V5d29yZD1OZ3V5JWUxJWJiJTg1bitIaSVlMSViYiU4MW4=&page=1|archivedate=2011-07-16}}</ref> ''b\u1ea3ng nh\u00e3n'' [[L\u00ea V\u0103n H\u01b0u]] who later became a royal historian of the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty,<ref name=lvh>{{cite encyclopedia|url=http://dictionary.bachkhoatoanthu.gov.vn/default.aspx?param=213AaWQ9MTU3NTgmZ3JvdXBpZD0ma2luZD1leGFjdCZrZXl3b3JkPUwlYzMlOGErViVjNCU4Mk4rSCVjNiVhZlU=&page=1|title=L\u00ea V\u0103n H\u01b0u|language=Vietnamese|encyclopedia=[[T\u1eeb \u0111i\u1ec3n B\u00e1ch khoa to\u00e0n th\u01b0 Vi\u1ec7t Nam]]|accessdate=2009-12-09|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716022010/http://dictionary.bachkhoatoanthu.gov.vn/default.aspx?param=213AaWQ9MTU3NTgmZ3JvdXBpZD0ma2luZD1leGFjdCZrZXl3b3JkPUwlYzMlOGErViVjNCU4Mk4rSCVjNiVhZlU=&page=1|archivedate=2011-07-16}}</ref> and ''th\u00e1m hoa'' [[\u0110\u1eb7ng Ma La]].{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=168}} In the 1256 examination, the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty divided the title ''tr\u1ea1ng nguy\u00ean'' into two categories, ''kinh tr\u1ea1ng nguy\u00ean'' for candidates from northern provinces and ''tr\u1ea1i tr\u1ea1ng nguy\u00ean'' for those from two southern provinces: [[Thanh H\u00f3a]] and [[Ngh\u1ec7 An]],{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=172}} so that students from those remote regions could have the motivation for the imperial examination. This separation was abolished in 1275 when the ruler decided that it was no longer necessary.{{sfn|Tr\u01b0\u01a1ng H\u1eefu Qu\u00fdnh, \u0110inh Xu\u00e2n L\u00e2m, L\u00ea M\u1eadu H\u00e3n|2008|p=261}}\n\nIn 1304, the Emperor Tr\u1ea7n Anh T\u00f4ng decided to standardize the examination by four different rounds in which candidates were eliminated step by step through tests of classical texts, [[Thirteen Classics|Confucianist classics]], royal document redaction, and finally argument and planning.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=217}} This examining process was abandoned in 1396 by the Emperor Tr\u1ea7n Thu\u1eadn T\u00f4ng under pressure from H\u1ed3 Qu\u00fd Ly, who replaced the traditional examination with the new version as a part of his radical reforms of the social and administrative system. H\u1ed3 Qu\u00fd Ly regulated the imperial examination by a prefectural examination (thi h\u01b0\u01a1ng) and a metropolitan examination (''thi h\u1ed9i'') following in the next year. The second-degree examination included four rounds: literary dissertation, literary composition, royal document redaction, and eventually an essay which was evaluated by the Emperor in person.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=289}} For the lower-ranking officials, the emperor had another examination which tested writing and calculating, such as the examination in the sixth lunar month of 1261 during the reign of Tr\u1ea7n Th\u00e1nh T\u00f4ng.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=176}}\n\nDuring its 175 years of existence, the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty carried out fourteen imperial examinations including ten official and four auxiliary contests. Many laureates from these examinations later became prominent officials in the royal court or well-known scholars such as L\u00ea V\u0103n H\u01b0u, author of the historical accounts ''[[\u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t s\u1eed k\u00fd]]'',<ref name=lvh/> M\u1ea1c \u0110\u0129nh Chi, renowned envoy of the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty to the Yuan dynasty,{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=233}} or [[Nguy\u1ec5n Trung Ng\u1ea1n]], one of the most powerful officials during the reign of Tr\u1ea7n Minh T\u00f4ng.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=233}} Below is the complete list of examinations with the candidates who ranked first in each examination:{{sfn|Mai H\u1ed3ng|1989|p=20}}\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Emperor\n!Ranked first\n!Note\n|-\n|1232 || style=\"background:#FFEFD5\"|Tr\u1ea7n Th\u00e1i T\u00f4ng || [[Tr\u01b0\u01a1ng Hanh]]<br>[[L\u01b0u Di\u1ec5m]] || {{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=163}}\n|-\n|1234 || style=\"background:#FFEFD5\"|Tr\u1ea7n Th\u00e1i T\u00f4ng || [[Nguy\u1ec5n Quan Quang]] || {{sfn|Mai H\u1ed3ng|1989|p=20}}\n|-\n|1239 || style=\"background:#FFEFD5\"|Tr\u1ea7n Th\u00e1i T\u00f4ng || [[L\u01b0u Mi\u1ec5n]]<br>[[V\u01b0\u01a1ng Gi\u00e1t]] || {{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=166}}\n|-\n|1247 || style=\"background:#FFEFD5\"|Tr\u1ea7n Th\u00e1i T\u00f4ng ||style=\"background:#E0FFFF\"| [[Nguy\u1ec5n Hi\u1ec1n]] ||style=\"background:#E0FFFF\"| ''Tr\u1ea1ng nguy\u00ean''{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=168}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1256 || rowspan=2 style=\"background:#FFEFD5\"|Tr\u1ea7n Th\u00e1i T\u00f4ng ||style=\"background:#E0FFFF\"| [[Tr\u1ea7n Qu\u1ed1c L\u1eb7c]] ||style=\"background:#E0FFFF\"| ''Kinh tr\u1ea1ng nguy\u00ean''{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=172}}\n|-\n|style=\"background:#B0E0E6\"|[[Tr\u01b0\u01a1ng X\u00e1n]] ||style=\"background:#B0E0E6\"| ''Tr\u1ea1i tr\u1ea1ng nguy\u00ean''{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=172}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1266 || rowspan=2 style=\"background:#FFE4B5\"|Tr\u1ea7n Th\u00e1nh T\u00f4ng ||style=\"background:#E0FFFF\"| [[Tr\u1ea7n C\u1ed1]] ||style=\"background:#E0FFFF\"| ''Kinh tr\u1ea1ng nguy\u00ean''{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=179}}\n|-\n|style=\"background:#B0E0E6\"|[[B\u1ea1ch Li\u00eau]] ||style=\"background:#B0E0E6\"| ''Tr\u1ea1i tr\u1ea1ng nguy\u00ean''{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=179}}\n|-\n|1272 ||style=\"background:#FFE4B5\"| Tr\u1ea7n Th\u00e1nh T\u00f4ng ||style=\"background:#E0FFFF\"| [[L\u00fd \u0110\u1ea1o T\u00e1i]] ||style=\"background:#E0FFFF\"| ''Tr\u1ea1ng nguy\u00ean''{{sfn|Mai H\u1ed3ng|1989|p=20}}\n|-\n|1275 ||style=\"background:#FFE4B5\"| Tr\u1ea7n Th\u00e1nh T\u00f4ng ||style=\"background:#E0FFFF\"| [[\u0110\u00e0o Ti\u00eau]] ||style=\"background:#E0FFFF\"| ''Tr\u1ea1ng nguy\u00ean''{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=182}}\n|-\n|1304 ||style=\"background:#FFDAB9\"| Tr\u1ea7n Anh T\u00f4ng ||style=\"background:#E0FFFF\"| [[M\u1ea1c \u0110\u0129nh Chi]] ||style=\"background:#E0FFFF\"| ''Tr\u1ea1ng nguy\u00ean''{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=217}}\n|-\n|1347 ||style=\"background:#EEE8AA\"| Tr\u1ea7n D\u1ee5 T\u00f4ng ||style=\"background:#E0FFFF\"| [[\u0110\u00e0o S\u01b0 T\u00edch]] ||style=\"background:#E0FFFF\"| ''Tr\u1ea1ng nguy\u00ean''{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=267}}\n|}\n\n==Science and technology==\n\nThere is evidence for the use of [[feng shui]] by Tr\u1ea7n dynasty officials, such as in 1248 when Tr\u1ea7n Th\u1ee7 \u0110\u1ed9 ordered several feng shui masters to block many spots over the country for the purpose of protecting the newly founded Tr\u1ea7n dynasty from its opponents.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=169}} Achievements in science during the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty were not detailed in historical accounts, though a notable scientist named [[\u0110\u1eb7ng L\u1ed9]] was mentioned several times in ''\u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t s\u1eed k\u00ed to\u00e0n th\u01b0''. It was said that \u0110\u1eb7ng L\u1ed9 was appointed by Retired Emperor Minh T\u00f4ng to the position of national inspector (''li\u00eam ph\u00f3ng s\u1ee9''){{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=234}} but he was noted for his invention called ''lung linh nghi'' which was a type of [[armillary sphere]] for astronomic measurement.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|url=http://dictionary.bachkhoatoanthu.gov.vn/default.aspx?param=1417aWQ9MzY2NjUmZ3JvdXBpZD05JmtpbmQ9JmtleXdvcmQ9&page=5|encyclopedia=[[T\u1eeb \u0111i\u1ec3n B\u00e1ch khoa to\u00e0n th\u01b0 Vi\u1ec7t Nam]]|title=\u0110\u1eb7ng L\u1ed9|language=Vietnamese|accessdate=2009-12-08|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716022052/http://dictionary.bachkhoatoanthu.gov.vn/default.aspx?param=1417aWQ9MzY2NjUmZ3JvdXBpZD05JmtpbmQ9JmtleXdvcmQ9&page=5|archivedate=2011-07-16}}</ref> From the result in observation, \u0110\u1eb7ng L\u1ed9 successfully persuaded the emperor to modify the calendar in 1339 for a better fit with the agricultural seasons in \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=246}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baobinhduong.org.vn/detailen.aspx?Item=2693 |language=Vietnamese |title=\u0110\u1eb7ng L\u1ed9: Nh\u00e0 thi\u00ean v\u0103n h\u1ecdc |publisher=Baobinhduong.org.vn |date=2006-02-28 |accessdate=2009-12-08 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Marquis [[Tr\u1ea7n Nguy\u00ean \u0110\u00e1n]], a superior of \u0110\u1eb7ng L\u1ed9 in the royal court, was also an expert in calendar calculation.<ref name=Tranbktt>{{cite encyclopedia|url=http://dictionary.bachkhoatoanthu.gov.vn/default.aspx?param=1A87aWQ9MTc3NCZncm91cGlkPSZraW5kPWV4YWN0JmtleXdvcmQ9VFIlZTElYmElYTZO&page=1|encyclopedia=[[T\u1eeb \u0111i\u1ec3n B\u00e1ch khoa to\u00e0n th\u01b0 Vi\u1ec7t Nam]]|title=Tr\u1ea7n|language=Vietnamese|accessdate=2009-12-08|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716022118/http://dictionary.bachkhoatoanthu.gov.vn/default.aspx?param=1A87aWQ9MTc3NCZncm91cGlkPSZraW5kPWV4YWN0JmtleXdvcmQ9VFIlZTElYmElYTZO&page=1|archivedate=2011-07-16}}</ref>\n\n=== Gunpowder ===\nNear the end of the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty the technology of [[gunpowder]] appeared in the historical records of \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t. It was responsible for the death of the King of Champa, Ch\u1ebf B\u1ed3ng Nga, after general Tr\u1ea7n Kh\u00e1t Ch\u00e2n fired a cannon from his battleship in January 1390.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4|1993|pp=282\u2013283}} According to the [[National University of Singapore|NUS]] researcher Sun Laichen, the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty acquired gunpowder technology from China and effectively used it to change the balance of power between \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t and Champa in favour of \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t.{{sfn|Tuyet Nhung Tran, Anthony J. S. Reid|2006|pp=75\u201377}} As a result of this Sun reasoned that the need for copper for manufacturing firearms was probably another reason for the order of H\u1ed3 Qu\u00fd Ly to change from copper coins to paper money in 1396. {{sfn|Tuyet Nhung Tran, Anthony J. S. Reid|2006|p=77}} The people of the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty and later H\u1ed3 dynasty continued to improve their firearms using gunpowder. This resulted in weapons of superior quality to their Chinese counterparts. These were acquired by the [[Ming dynasty]] in their [[Fourth Chinese domination (History of Vietnam)|invasion of \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t]].{{sfn|Tuyet Nhung Tran, Anthony J. S. Reid|2006|pp=89\u201390}}\n\n=== Medicine ===\n[[File:National Museum Vietnamese History 29 (cropped).jpg|thumb|Patterned brown glazed ceramic jar with lotus and chrysanthemum motifs from Nam \u0110\u1ecbnh Province (13th\u201314th century)]] \nDuring the rule of the Tr\u1ea7n dynasty, medicine had a better chance to develop because of a more significant role of Confucianism in society.{{sfn|Alan Kam-leung Chan, Gregory K. Clancey,Hui-Chieh Loy|2001|p=265}}<ref name=Jan>{{cite book|title=Oriental medicine: an illustrated guide to the Asian arts of healing|author1=Jan Van Alphen |author2=Anthony Aris |year=1995|publisher=Serindia Publications, Inc.|isbn=0-906026-36-9|pages=210\u2013214}}</ref> In 1261,{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=176}} the emperor issued an order to establish the Institute of Royal Physicians (Th\u00e1i y vi\u1ec7n) which managed medicine in \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t, carrying out the examination for new physicians and treating people during disease epidemics.{{sfn|Alan Kam-leung Chan, Gregory K. Clancey,Hui-Chieh Loy|2001|p=265}} In 1265 the institute distributed a pill named ''H\u1ed3ng ng\u1ecdc s\u01b0\u01a1ng'' to the poor, which they considered able to cure many diseases.{{sfn|Ng\u00f4 S\u0129 Li\u00ean|1993|p=257}} Besides the traditional [[Chinese herbology|Northern herbs]] (''thu\u1ed1c B\u1eafc''), Tr\u1ea7n physicians also began to cultivate and gather various regional medicinal herbs (''thu\u1ed1c Nam'') for treating both civilians and soldiers. During the reign of Tr\u1ea7n Minh T\u00f4ng the head of the Institute of Royal Physicians [[Ph\u1ea1m C\u00f4ng B\u00e2n]] was widely known for his medical ethics, treating patients regardless of their descent with his own medicine made from regional herbs;{{sfn|Alan Kam-leung Chan, Gregory K. Clancey,Hui-Chieh Loy|2001|p=265}}{{sfn|Ph\u1ea1m V\u0103n S\u01a1n|1983|p=215}} it was said that Ph\u1ea1m C\u00f4ng B\u00e2n gathered his remedies in a medical book named ''Th\u00e1i y d\u1ecbch b\u1ec7nh'' (''Diseases by the Royal Physician'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.haiduongdost.gov.vn/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=748:y-hc-c-truyn-ca-tnh-hi-dng-trong-hin-ti-va-tng-lai&catid=107:lvyt&Itemid=169|title=Y h\u1ecdc c\u1ed5 truy\u1ec1n c\u1ee7a t\u1ec9nh H\u1ea3i D\u01b0\u01a1ng trong hi\u1ec7n t\u1ea1i v\u00e0 t\u01b0\u01a1ng lai|language=Vietnamese|author=Nguy\u1ec5n Xu\u00e2n Vi\u1ec7t|publisher=Haiduong Department of Science and Technology|date=2008-12-26|accessdate=2009-12-09|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Fz04XLVw?url=http://www.haiduongdost.gov.vn/index.php?option=com_content|archivedate=2013-04-19}}</ref>\n\nAnother Tr\u1ea7n person and fellow countryman of Ph\u1ea1m C\u00f4ng B\u00e2n was the monk [[Tu\u1ec7 T\u0129nh]], one of the most famous physicians in Vietnamese history, who was called \"Father of the Southern Medicine\" for creating the basis of Vietnamese traditional medicine with his works ''H\u1ed3ng ngh\u0129a gi\u00e1c t\u01b0 y th\u01b0'' and ''Nam d\u01b0\u1ee3c th\u1ea7n hi\u1ec7u''.<ref name=\"tuetinh\">{{cite encyclopedia|url=http://dictionary.bachkhoatoanthu.gov.vn/default.aspx?param=1E6CaWQ9MjQ1OSZncm91cGlkPSZraW5kPWV4YWN0JmtleXdvcmQ9VFUlZTElYmIlODYrVCVjNCVhOE5I&page=1|title=Tu\u1ec7 T\u0129nh|language=Vietnamese|encyclopedia=[[T\u1eeb \u0111i\u1ec3n B\u00e1ch khoa to\u00e0n th\u01b0 Vi\u1ec7t Nam]]|accessdate=2009-12-09|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716022026/http://dictionary.bachkhoatoanthu.gov.vn/default.aspx?param=1E6CaWQ9MjQ1OSZncm91cGlkPSZraW5kPWV4YWN0JmtleXdvcmQ9VFUlZTElYmIlODYrVCVjNCVhOE5I&page=1|archivedate=2011-07-16}}</ref> ''Nam d\u01b0\u1ee3c th\u1ea7n hi\u1ec7u'' was a collection of 499 manuscripts about local herbs and ten branches of treatment with 3932 prescriptions to cure 184 type of diseases while ''H\u1ed3ng ngh\u0129a gi\u00e1c t\u01b0 y th\u01b0'' provided people with many simple, easy-to-prepare medicines with high effect.<ref name=\"tuetinh\" />{{sfn|Alan Kam-leung Chan, Gregory K. Clancey,Hui-Chieh Loy|2001|pp=265\u2013266}}\n\n==Timeline of emperors==\n{| cellpadding=3 cellspacing=2 style=\"float:right; margin:5px; border:3px solid;\"\n|-\n|colspan=2 align=center | <timeline>\n# All measures all in pixels\nImageSize  = width:170 height:610\nPlotArea   = width: 26 height:560 left:40 bottom:40\nAlignBars  = late\n\nDateFormat = yyyy\nPeriod     = from:1226 till:1400\nTimeAxis   = orientation:vertical order:reverse\nScaleMajor = unit:year increment:10 start:1226\n# there is no automatic collision detection,\n# so shift texts up or down manually to avoid overlap\n\nDefine $dx = 25 # shift text to right side of bar\n\nLegend  = columns:1 left:20 top:40 columnwidth:100\n\nColors =\n id:other value:orange\n id:usurp value:red legend:Usurp\nPlotData=\n  bar:Leaders width:25 mark:(line,white) align:left fontsize:S\n  from:1226 till:1258 shift:($dx,-3) color:other text:[[Tr\u1ea7n Th\u00e1i T\u00f4ng|Th\u00e1i T\u00f4ng]]\n  from:1258 till:1278 shift:($dx,-3) color:other text:[[Tr\u1ea7n Th\u00e1nh T\u00f4ng|Th\u00e1nh T\u00f4ng]]\n  from:1278 till:1293 shift:($dx,-3) color:other text:[[Tr\u1ea7n Nh\u00e2n T\u00f4ng|Nh\u00e2n T\u00f4ng]]\n  from:1293 till:1314 shift:($dx,-3) color:other text:[[Tr\u1ea7n Anh T\u00f4ng|Anh T\u00f4ng]]\n  from:1314 till:1329 shift:($dx,-3) color:other text:[[Tr\u1ea7n Minh T\u00f4ng|Minh T\u00f4ng]]\n  from:1329 till:1341 shift:($dx,-3) color:other text:[[Tr\u1ea7n Hi\u1ebfn T\u00f4ng|Hi\u1ebfn T\u00f4ng]]\n  from:1341 till:1369 shift:($dx,-3) color:other text:[[Tr\u1ea7n D\u1ee5 T\u00f4ng|D\u1ee5 T\u00f4ng]]\n  from:1369 till:1370 shift:($dx,-3) color:usurp text:[[H\u00f4n \u0110\u1ee9c C\u00f4ng]]\n  from:1370 till:1372 shift:($dx,-3) color:other text:[[Tr\u1ea7n Ngh\u1ec7 T\u00f4ng|Ngh\u1ec7 T\u00f4ng]]\n  from:1372 till:1377 shift:($dx,-3) color:other text:[[Tr\u1ea7n Du\u1ec7 T\u00f4ng|Du\u1ec7 T\u00f4ng]]\n  from:1377 till:1388 shift:($dx,-3) color:other text:[[Tr\u1ea7n Ph\u1ebf \u0110\u1ebf|Ph\u1ebf \u0110\u1ebf]]\n  from:1388 till:1398 shift:($dx,-3) color:other text:[[Tr\u1ea7n Thu\u1eadn T\u00f4ng|Thu\u1eadn T\u00f4ng]]\n  from:1398 till:1400 shift:($dx,-3) color:other text:[[Tr\u1ea7n Thi\u1ebfu \u0110\u1ebf|Thi\u1ebfu \u0110\u1ebf]]\n</timeline>\n|-\n|}\n{{familytree/start}}\n{{familytree | | | | | | | | | TTT | | | | | | | | | | | | | | TTT=[[Tr\u1ea7n Th\u1eeba|Th\u00e1i T\u1ed5]]}}\n{{familytree | | | | | | | | | |!| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | }}\n{{familytree | | | | | | | | | TTT | | | | | | | | | | | | | | TTT=[[Tr\u1ea7n Th\u00e1i T\u00f4ng|Th\u00e1i T\u00f4ng]]}}\n{{familytree | | | | | | | | | |!| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | }}\n{{familytree | | | | | | | | | TTT | | | | | | | | | | | | | | TTT=[[Tr\u1ea7n Th\u00e1nh T\u00f4ng|Th\u00e1nh T\u00f4ng]]}}\n{{familytree | | | | | | | | | |!| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | }}\n{{familytree | | | | | | | | | TNT | | | | | | | | | | | | | | TNT=[[Tr\u1ea7n Nh\u00e2n T\u00f4ng|Nh\u00e2n T\u00f4ng]]}}\n{{familytree | | | | | | | | | |!| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | }}\n{{familytree | | | | | | | | | TAT | | | | | | | | | | | | | | TAT=[[Tr\u1ea7n Anh T\u00f4ng|Anh T\u00f4ng]]}}\n{{familytree | | | | | | | | | |!| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | }}\n{{familytree | | | | | | | | | TMT | | | | | | | | | | | | | | TMT=[[Tr\u1ea7n Minh T\u00f4ng|Minh T\u00f4ng]]}}\n{{familytree | |,|-|-|-|-|v|-|-|^|-|-|v|-|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|-|.| | }}\n{{familytree | TNT | | | THT | | | | TDT | | | TD2 | | | CDV | TNT=[[Tr\u1ea7n Ngh\u1ec7 T\u00f4ng|Ngh\u1ec7 T\u00f4ng]]|THT=[[Tr\u1ea7n Hi\u1ebfn T\u00f4ng|Hi\u1ebfn T\u00f4ng]]|TDT=[[Tr\u1ea7n D\u1ee5 T\u00f4ng|D\u1ee5 T\u00f4ng]]|TD2=[[Tr\u1ea7n Du\u1ec7 T\u00f4ng|Du\u1ec7 T\u00f4ng]]|CDV=[[Tr\u1ea7n D\u1ee5c|Cung T\u00fac]]}}\n{{familytree | |!| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |!| | | | |!| | }}\n{{familytree | TTT | | | | | | | | | | | | | | TPD | | | DNL | TTT=[[Tr\u1ea7n Thu\u1eadn T\u00f4ng|Thu\u1eadn T\u00f4ng]]|TPD=[[Tr\u1ea7n Ph\u1ebf \u0110\u1ebf|Ph\u1ebf \u0110\u1ebf]]|